From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-27
Subject: [I3] Move `claude plugin marketplace add` from Dockerfile build
         to postCreateCommand so the volume mount doesn't shadow it

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside
the container, so an agent running inside cannot edit Dockerfile or
post_install.py directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any
environment with write access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

**Order of application:** apply
`2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-and-hardening.patch` (the
sibling C1/C2/I2/I4/S1/S2/S4/LAT2 patch) FIRST. This patch's
post_install.py hunk is rebased on top of that one; applying in the
reverse order will conflict around `main()`.

What this fixes (review item I3)
================================
Three `claude plugin marketplace add` calls run during the Dockerfile's
RUN layer (Dockerfile:94-97), writing into `/home/vscode/.claude`. But
devcontainer.json mounts a named volume at exactly that path. Docker's
"populate empty named volume from image dir" rule applies only to
*empty* volumes; on container rebuild without `docker volume rm` (the
default for VS Code "Rebuild Container"), the existing volume contents
shadow the image dir entirely.

Symptom: marketplace pin updates don't propagate to existing
developers. The registrations baked at first-build work on initial
creation but stop reflecting Dockerfile changes after that — silent
staleness, no error.

Fix: move the calls into a new `setup_plugin_marketplaces()` function
in post_install.py, which runs as `postCreateCommand`. By then the
volume is mounted and writes land in the volume, so registrations
apply on every container creation. `claude plugin marketplace add` is
idempotent — re-adding an already-registered marketplace is a no-op.

Trust-posture commentary that previously sat above the Dockerfile RUN
line (the third-party-marketplace caveat, NET_ADMIN/bypassPermissions
blast-radius note, hardening checklist) is migrated into the new
function's docstring so it stays adjacent to the actual call.

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-and-hardening.patch
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-marketplace-runtime-add.patch
  git add .devcontainer/post_install.py .devcontainer/Dockerfile
  git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): register plugin marketplaces at postCreate, not build (I3)"

Then push.

---
--- a/.devcontainer/post_install.py
+++ b/.devcontainer/post_install.py
@@ -572,6 +572,68 @@
         )
 
 
+def setup_plugin_marketplaces():
+    """Register Claude plugin marketplaces.
+
+    I3 (review 2026-04-27): previously added at image-build time in
+    the Dockerfile. The volume mount at /home/vscode/.claude shadows
+    the image's `~/.claude` on container creation when the named
+    volume is non-empty (i.e. every "Reopen in Container" except the
+    very first), so build-time registrations stop reflecting
+    Dockerfile changes once the volume is initialized — silently
+    stale. Run them at postCreateCommand time instead so they apply
+    after the volume mount, on every container creation. `claude
+    plugin marketplace add` is idempotent — re-adding an already-
+    registered marketplace is a no-op.
+
+    Trust posture (carried over from the prior Dockerfile comment):
+    `anthropics/skills` is Anthropic-controlled and consistent with
+    trusting the Claude CLI itself. The two `trailofbits/...` entries
+    are third-party — a compromise of either upstream lands plugin
+    code that Claude can invoke. Combined with bypassPermissions
+    (when opted in via SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS), NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW
+    caps, and the R/W workspace mount, plugin compromise has a wide
+    blast radius. The CLI does not (yet) expose a SHA-pinning
+    mechanism we can wire in here.
+
+    Hardening checklist when revisiting:
+      - Drop any marketplace whose plugins you do not actively invoke
+      - When the CLI gains pin support, wire it up (one-line discipline)
+      - Track which plugins you call from each marketplace so future
+        drops are mechanical
+    """
+    marketplaces = [
+        "anthropics/skills",
+        "trailofbits/skills",
+        "trailofbits/skills-curated",
+    ]
+    for mp in marketplaces:
+        try:
+            r = subprocess.run(
+                ["claude", "plugin", "marketplace", "add", mp],
+                capture_output=True,
+                text=True,
+                timeout=30,
+            )
+            if r.returncode == 0:
+                print(
+                    f"[post_install] Plugin marketplace registered: {mp}",
+                    file=sys.stderr,
+                )
+            else:
+                print(
+                    f"[post_install] Warning: `claude plugin marketplace add "
+                    f"{mp}` exited {r.returncode}: {r.stderr.strip()}",
+                    file=sys.stderr,
+                )
+        except (OSError, subprocess.SubprocessError) as e:
+            print(
+                f"[post_install] Warning: could not register marketplace "
+                f"{mp} ({e})",
+                file=sys.stderr,
+            )
+
+
 def main():
     """Run all post-install configuration."""
     print("[post_install] Starting post-install configuration...", file=sys.stderr)
@@ -584,6 +646,7 @@
     fix_directory_ownership()
     setup_onboarding_bypass()
     setup_claude_settings()
+    setup_plugin_marketplaces()
     setup_tmux_config()
     setup_global_gitignore()
 
